abstract: At nearly nine p.m. on Saturday, Samy Amkieh was about to head back to his office after braving 20 degree temperatures to knock on doors for three hours in East Des Moines. But the 20-year-old field organizer knocked on one more door and was rewarded by convincing the resident to be a team leader for Bernie Sanders at a nearby caucus location.

lead_paragraph: ANKENY, Iowa — At nearly nine p.m. on Saturday, Samy Amkieh was about to head back to his office after braving 20 degree temperatures to knock on doors for three hours in East Des Moines. But the 20-year-old field organizer knocked on one more door and was rewarded by convincing the resident to be a team leader for Bernie Sanders at a nearby caucus location.
headline_main: Organization Becomes Critical in Final Week Before Iowa Vote
headline_print_headline: Organization Becomes Critical in Final Week Before Iowa Vote

abstract: The candidates were in Iowa, but in Washington there was a major impeachment development.

lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — News that President Trump told John Bolton, the former national security adviser, that he wanted to continue freezing aid to Ukraine until officials there helped with investigations into Democrats including the Biden family rippled through the campaign trail in Iowa on Sunday night.
headline_main: The Bolton revelation sinks in on the campaign trail.

lead_paragraph: WEST DES MOINES — What’s it like to be a still-undecided Iowa Democrat eight days before the state’s first-in-the-nation presidential caucuses?
headline_main: ‘I’m really up in the air’: some Iowans are still undecided.

abstract: The current system is a form of white privilege that warps the process.
snippet: The current system is a form of white privilege that warps the process.
lead_paragraph: The Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary owe their first-in-the-nation status partly to circumstance. Decades ago, Iowa’s caucus was the initial step in a long, complex process that the state used to award delegates, which meant that the voting had to happen early in the year. New Hampshire was mostly trying to save money — by scheduling its primary on the same day as many annual town meetings, which were held before the spring mud season.

abstract: The candidates gave their stump speeches. They took photos and shook hands. They tried mightily to address the polling elephant in the room without appearing to concern themselves with it.
snippet: The candidates gave their stump speeches. They took photos and shook hands. They tried mightily to address the polling elephant in the room without appearing to concern themselves with it.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — With the Iowa caucuses a week away and senators briefly sprung from their impeachment-induced confinement on Capitol Hill, the Democratic presidential candidates and their surrogates spilled out across Iowa on Sunday.

abstract: In the limited time he has to spend on the trail during the impeachment trial, Mr. Bennet plans to campaign solely in New Hampshire.
snippet: In the limited time he has to spend on the trail during the impeachment trial, Mr. Bennet plans to campaign solely in New Hampshire.
lead_paragraph: Senator Michael Bennet of Colorado told New Hampshire’s WMUR television station on Sunday that he would campaign only in New Hampshire through the primary there — even on the day of the Iowa caucuses.
headline_main: Michael Bennet is done with Iowa.

abstract: During one of several campaign stops in Iowa before leaving for the impeachment trial, Amy Klobuchar focused on health care and drug prices.
snippet: During one of several campaign stops in Iowa before leaving for the impeachment trial, Amy Klobuchar focused on health care and drug prices.
lead_paragraph: AMES, Iowa — It was, well, a re-endorsement, one that David Johnson, the former Iowa state senator who disavowed the Republican Party after it nominated Donald J. Trump in 2016, drove more than two hours to make.
headline_main: Klobuchar prepares to ‘turn into a pumpkin’ and return to Washington.

abstract: Over the past week, Democratic candidates have spent over $3.5 million in the four main TV markets in the state.
snippet: Over the past week, Democratic candidates have spent over $3.5 million in the four main TV markets in the state.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — It’s the final sprint in Iowa, but with three top candidates spending much of the past week in Washington as jurors for President Trump’s impeachment trial, televisions here in Iowa have been inundated with political ads to help provide air cover in this bifurcated political moment.
headline_main: Political ads are flooding Iowa. What do they say?
